@node "Introduction" "Introduction"
@{par}
  @{b}@{u}Introduction@{uu}@{ub}@{par}

@{lindent 2}- Do you use programs that have ugly AppIcons?@{lindent 0}@{par}
@{lindent 2}- Do you want a program to have another AppIcon image, but you can't change
it?@{lindent 0}@{par}
@{lindent 2}- You don't like an AppIcon's title, but there's no way to satisfy your
needs?@{lindent 0}@{par}
@{lindent 2}- You want an AppIcon to appear on another position, but you aren't able to
fix it?@{lindent 0}@{par}

Well, here's the final solution for all these problems.@{par}

With NewAppIcon, you can change *every* AppIcon to meet your dreams!@{par}
Replace those awful built-in AppIcons with your preferred ones!@{par}

@endnode

@node "PrefsEd" "Preferences editor"
@{par}
  @{lindent 2}@{b}@{u}Preferences editor@{uu}@{ub}@{lindent 0}@{par}

I am currently thinking about creating a nice MUI-based preferences editor.
This editor will of course be freeware, but I am not sure if it will be
worth this work because I don't know how many people actually use
NewAppIcon.@{par}

If you think you would like to have a preferences editor for NewAppIcon,
please leave @{"me" link "Author"} a short e-mail. I would also appreciate any comments, bug
reports and recommendations for NewAppIcon.@{par}


(As of release 1.5 of NewAppIcon, only 3 users e-mailed me so far...)@{par}

@endnode

@node "Usage" "Usage"
@{par}
  @{b}@{u}Usage@{uu}@{ub}@{par}

NewAppIcon can be started from the Shell or the Workbench (but preferably
from s:Startup-Sequence right after SetPatch).@{par}

@{lindent 22}@{b}Template:  @{ub}NewAppIcon CONFIG=-c/K, SNOOP=-s/S, QUIT=-q/S,
RELOAD=-r/S, SNOOPON=-so/S, SNOOPOFF=-sf/S@{lindent 0}@{par}

You should run NewAppIcon with "@{i}Run >NIL: <NIL: NewAppIcon ...@{ui}".@{par}


@{u}Parameters:@{uu}@{par}

@{lindent 11}@{b}CONFIG   @{ub}- You can specify a path to your preferred configuration file here.
If you omit this parameter, NewAppIcon will open the file
@{i}ENV:NewAppIcon.cfg@{ui}.@{par}
See the supplied @{"configuration file" link "/NewAppIcon.cfg/Main"} for details.@{lindent 0}@{par}

@{lindent 11}@{b}SNOOP    @{ub}- This option turns the snoop mode on. Whenever a program wants to
add an AppIcon to the Workbench, you will be prompted with a
requester showing the icon title and the task name. This is useful
if you want to add entries to your configuration file.@{lindent 0}@{par}

@{lindent 11}@{b}QUIT     @{ub}- This parameter can be used to signal a running NewAppIcon instance
to quit itself.@{par}
Specifying this parameter will result in not running another
instance of NewAppIcon, ie. it will immediately quit after
signalling the current running NewAppIcon instance.@{par}
This parameter cannot be used together with RELOAD, SNOOPON and/or SNOOPOFF.@{lindent 0}@{par}

@{lindent 11}@{b}RELOAD   @{ub}- This parameter can be used to signal a running NewAppIcon instance
to reload its preferences.@{par}
Specifying this parameter will result in not running another
instance of NewAppIcon, ie. it will immediately quit after
signalling the current running NewAppIcon instance.@{par}
This parameter cannot be used together with QUIT.@{lindent 0}@{par}

@{lindent 11}@{b}SNOOPON  @{ub}- This parameter can be used to signal a running NewAppIcon instance
to turn its snoop mode on.
Specifying this parameter will result in not running another
instance of NewAppIcon, ie. it will immediately quit after
signalling the current running NewAppIcon instance.@{par}
This parameter cannot be used together with QUIT and/or SNOOPOFF.@{lindent 0}@{par}

@{lindent 11}@{b}SNOOPOFF @{ub}- This parameter can be used to signal a running NewAppIcon instance
to turn its snoop mode off.
Specifying this parameter will result in not running another
instance of NewAppIcon, ie. it will immediately quit after
signalling the current running NewAppIcon instance.@{par}
This parameter cannot be used together with QUIT and/or SNOOPON.@{lindent 0}@{par}


@{lindent 9}Notes: - You can remove all NewAppIcon patches safely by sending a CTRL+C to
its task (you could use "@{i}Break `Status COMMAND NewAppIcon`@{ui}" to do
this). You can also use the QUIT parameter mentioned above.@{par}
You should also consider installing SetMan 2.0+ which can be found on Aminet
in util/boot/setman20.lha.@{lindent 7}@{par}
@{lindent 9}- NewAppIcon won't eat up *any* CPU time until AppIcons are added or
removed from/to the Workbench!@{lindent 0}@{par}

@endnode
@node "NewAppIconStat" "NewAppIconStat"
@{par}
  @{b}@{u}NewAppIconStat@{uu}@{ub}@{par}

NewAppIconStat is a tool which can display some statistics about the
activities of NewAppIcon. It can be started from the Shell or the Workbench.@{par}

@{lindent 11}@{b}Template:  @{ub}NewAppIconStat PREFS=-p/S@{lindent 0}@{par}


@{u}Parameters:@{uu}@{par}

@{lindent 8}@{b}PREFS @{ub}- Shows the contents of the current loaded preferences file.@{par}
If you omit this parameter, you will get a nice statistic about
NewAppIcon's activities.@{lindent 0}@{par}

@endnode
@node "Compatibility" "Compatibility"
@{par}
  @{b}@{u}Compatibility@{uu}@{ub}@{par}

@{lindent 2}- If you have Directory Opus running as a Workbench replacement, you should
start NewAppIcon from SYS:WBStartup/. This is because DOpus replaces the
original system AppIcon routines and therefore any patches to these
routines must be installed afterwards.@{lindent 0}@{par}

@endnode

@node "History" "History"
@{par}
  @{b}@{u}History@{uu}@{ub}@{par}

1.0, 07-Jul-1997:@{par}
@{lindent 4}  - first version of NewAppIcon@{lindent 0}@{par}

1.1, 09-Jul-1997:@{par}
@{lindent 4}  - more safety to patch remove routine added@{lindent 0}@{par}
@{lindent 4}  - PoolWatch hits completely eliminated@{lindent 0}@{par}
@{lindent 4}  - @{"NewAppIconStat tool" link "NewAppIconStat"} added@{lindent 0}@{par}

1.2, 14-Jul-1997:@{par}
@{lindent 4}  - AppIcons' names can now be replaced, too (see @{"NEWTITLE" link "/NewAppIcon.cfg/Main"} option)!@{lindent 0}@{par}
@{lindent 4}  - errors are now shown in a system requester if there is no interactive
output available (eg. started from WorkBench) @{lindent 0}@{par}
@{lindent 4}  - NewAppIcon can be signalled to quit itself or to reload its preferences
(see @{"QUIT" link "Usage"} and @{"RELOAD" link "Usage"} parameters)@{lindent 0}@{par}
@{lindent 4}  - NewAppIconStat can show preferences file contents now (see
@{"PREFS" link "NewAppIconStat"} parameter)@{lindent 0}@{par}
@{lindent 4}  - starting NewAppIcon from Workbench will no longer produce any output in
a CON window (extremely useful for starting from WBStartup)@{lindent 0}@{par}
@{lindent 4}  - the ORIGINAL parameter (in the configuration file) has been removed;
I really don't know why I implemented it... Please remove it from
your configuration files completely; it will not work anymore.@{lindent 0}@{par}
@{lindent 4}  - included @{"Compatibility section" link "Compatibility"} in documentation@{lindent 0}@{par}

1.3, 25-Jul-1997:@{par}
@{lindent 4}  - you can now have fixed AppIcon positions instead of original ones
(see @{"XPOS" link "/NewAppIcon.cfg/Main"} and @{"YPOS" link "/NewAppIcon.cfg/Main"} parameters)@{lindent 0}@{par}
@{lindent 4}  - included @{"Preferences editor section" link "PrefsEd"} in documentation@{lindent 0}@{par}

1.4, 22-Mar-1998:@{par}
@{lindent 4}  - NewAppIcon now takes care of SetMan installed (Aminet:util/boot/setman20.lha)@{lindent 0}@{par}
@{lindent 4}  - NewAppIcon can be signalled to turn its snoop mode on/off
(see @{"SNOOPON" link "Usage"} and @{"SNOOPOFF" link "Usage"} parameters)@{lindent 0}@{par}

1.5, 27-Jul-1998:@{par}
@{lindent 4}  - you are now able to insert the AppIcon's original title into a @{"NEWTITLE" link "Usage"}
parameter string@{lindent 0}@{par}
@{lindent 4}  - signalling NewAppIcon didn't work sometimes (see @{"QUIT" link "Usage"}, @{"RELOAD" link "Usage"}, @{"SNOOPON" link "Usage"} and
@{"SNOOPOFF" link "Usage"} parameters)@{lindent 0}@{par}

@endnode

